05370nam a22004815i 9780226210773DE-B159720210421021438.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210421t20212001ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802262107737 a10.7208/97802262107732doi  a(DE-B1597)575456  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aP94.5.A372 -- U55 2001eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a302.23/089/00973a302.23089960731 aEntman, Robert M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Black Image in the White Mind :bMedia and Race in America /cAndrew Rojecki, Robert M. Entman. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (340 p.) :b7 line drawings, 27 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Communication, Media, and Public Opinion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables and Figures -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Racial Chameleon -- t2. White Racial Attitudes in the Heartland -- t3. Culture, Media, and the White Mind: The Character of Their Content -- t4. The Meaning ofBlackness in Network News -- t5. Violence, Stereotypes, and African Americans in the News -- t6. Benign Neglect in the Poverty of the News -- t7. Affirming Discord -- t8. Black Power -- t9. Prime-TimeTelevision: White and Whiter -- t10. Advertising Whiteness -- t11. Race atthe Movies -- t12. Reflecting on the End ofRacial Representation -- tAppendix: Data Tables -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLiving in a segregated society, white Americans learn about African Americans not through personal relationships but through the images the media show them. The Black Image in the White Mind offers the most comprehensive look at the intricate racial patterns in the mass media and how they shape the ambivalent attitudes of Whites toward Blacks. Using the media, and especially television, as barometers of race relations, Robert Entman and Andrew Rojecki explore but then go beyond the treatment of African Americans on network and local news to incisively uncover the messages sent about race by the entertainment industry-from prime-time dramas and sitcoms to commercials and Hollywood movies. While the authors find very little in the media that intentionally promotes racism, they find even less that advances racial harmony. They reveal instead a subtle pattern of images that, while making room for Blacks, implies a racial hierarchy with Whites on top and promotes a sense of difference and conflict. Commercials, for example, feature plenty of Black characters. But unlike Whites, they rarely speak to or touch one another. In prime time, the few Blacks who escape sitcom buffoonery rarely enjoy informal, friendly contact with White colleagues-perhaps reinforcing social distance in real life. Entman and Rojecki interweave such astute observations with candid interviews of White Americans that make clear how these images of racial difference insinuate themselves into Whites' thinking. Despite its disturbing readings of television and film, the book's cogent analyses and proposed policy guidelines offer hope that America's powerful mediated racial separation can be successfully bridged. "Entman and Rojecki look at how television news focuses on black poverty and crime out of proportion to the material reality of black lives, how black 'experts' are only interviewed for 'black-themed' issues and how 'black politics' are distorted in the news, and conclude that, while there are more images of African-Americans on television now than there were years ago, these images often don't reflect a commitment to 'racial comity' or community-building between the races. Thoroughly researched and convincingly argued."-Publishers Weekly "Drawing on their own research and that of a wide array of other scholars, Entman and Rojecki present a great deal of provocative data showing a general tendency to devalue blacks or force them into stock categories."-Ben Yagoda, New Leader Winner of the Frank Luther Mott Award for best book in Mass Communication and the Robert E. Lane Award for best book in political psychology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aRojecki, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226210773423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226210773.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles